 for why certain areas experienced less volatility than others. It then examines the causes of the boom and bust, including the availability of credit, the perceived risk reduction due to the securitization of mortgages, and the increase in lending from foreign sources. Finally, it examines a range of policies that might address some of the sources of recent instability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFinancial crises -- United States -- History -- 21st century -- Congresses. 0aFinancial criseszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st centuryvCongresses. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009 -- Congresses. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009vCongresses. 0aHousing -- United States -- Finance -- Congresses. 0aHousingzUnited StatesxFinancevCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  ahousing market, financial crisis, boom and bust, economics, investment, debt, economy, net worth, wealth gap, middle class, nonfiction, finance, assets, construction, credit, risk, lending, mortgages, second liens, financing, history, capital flows, international lenders, foreign exchange, government, regulation, intervention, banking, politics, instability.1 aFavilukis, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenesove, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaeser, Edward L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaeser, Edward L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGottlieb, Joshua D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyourko, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Lu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaughwout, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb